abstract-rendering.description: Abstract Rendering is a bin-based rendering technique that provides greater control over a visual representation and access to larger data sets via server-side processing. Abstract rendering exposes the pixels and gives powerful pixel-level control, complementing many existing visualization techniques.

affine.description: The Affine package is used to produce the affine transformation matrix.
affine.summary: Matrices describing affine transformation of the plane.

alabaster.description: Alabaster is a visually clean, responsive, and configurable Sphinx theme. It is sidebar-enabled and easy to install/use as a Python package. As of Sphinx 1.3, Alabaster is selected as the default theme for Sphinx.

anaconda-build.description: Anaconda Build is a command line client that provides an interface to the Anaconda Cloud build system.

anaconda-client.description: Anaconda Client is a command line client that provides an interface to Anaconda cloud.

anaconda-verify.summary: tool for (passively) verifying conda recipes and conda packages

ansi2html.description: ansi2html allows users to convert text with ANSI color codes to HTML or to Latex.
ansi2html.summary: Convert text with ANSI color codes to HTML or to LaTeX.

appnope.description: Appnope is an easy way to disable and re-enable App Nap, a potentially problematic energy feature, in OS X 10.9.
appnope.summary: Disable App Nap on OS X 10.9

appscript.description: Appscript is a user-friendly Apple event bridge that allows users to control Applescriptable Mac OS X applications from Python. This allows Python to be a serious alternative to using Apple's AppleScript language.

apr.description: Apache Portable Runtime (APR) maintains software libraries that provides a consistent interface regardless of the platform on which software is built.
apr.summary: Maintains a consistent API with predictable behaviour

argcomplete.description: Argcomplete is an extensible command line tab completion of arguments for Python scripts. It requires users to use bash or zsh as their shell, and to use argparse to manage their command line arguments.
argcomplete.summary: Bash tab completion of arguments for Python scripts

astroid.description: Asteroid provides a common base representation of Python source code for various projects. It provides a compatible representation which comes from the _ast module. It includes support for static inference and local name scopes.
astroid.summary: abstract syntax tree for Python with inference support

astropy.description: The Astropy Project is a community effort to develop a single package for Astronomy in Python. It contains core functionality and common tools needed for performing astronomy and astrophysics research with Python.

atom.description: Atom is a framework for creating memory efficient Python objects with enhanced features such as dynamic initialization, validation, and change notification for object attributes.
atom.summary: Framework for creating memory efficient Python objects

attrs.description: Attrs eases the chores of implementing the most common attribute-related object protocols.
attrs.summary: Implement attribute-related object protocols without boilerplate

azure.description: Azure provides Python packages that make it easy to access Microsoft Azure components.

babel.description: Babel is an integrated collection of utilities that assist in internationalizing and localizing Python applications, with an emphasis on web-base applications.
babel.summary: Utilities to internationalize and localize Python applications

backports_abc.summary: backport of recent additions to the 'collections.abc' module

basemap.description: Basemap is a toolkit for matplotlib that allows you to plot 2D data on maps in Python. Basemap is geared toward the needs of Earth scientists, particularly oceanographers and meteorologists.
basemap.summary: Plot data on map projections with matplotlib

bcolz.description: bcolz provides columnar, chunked data containers that can be compressed in-memory or on-disk. It is based in NumPy but also comes with support for HDF5/PyTables tables and Pandas dataframes.
bcolz.summary: provides columnar, chunked and compressable data containers.

bcrypt.summary: modern password hashing for your software and your servers

beautifulsoup4.description: Beautiful Soup is a library for pulling data out of HTML and XML files. It provides ways of navigating, searching, and modifying parse trees.

biopython.description: Biopython is a set of freely available Python tools for computational molecular biology. Biopython makes it easy to use Python for bionformatics with high-quality, reusable modules and classes.
biopython.summary: Freely available tools for biological computation

bitarray.description: Bitarray provides an object type which efficiently represents an array of booleans. Bitarrays are sequence types that behave very similarly to usual lists. All functionality is implemented in C.
bitarray.summary: efficient representation of arrays of booleans -- C extension

blaze.description: The Blaze Ecosystem provides high-level access to efficient computation on large data. It contains a set of libraries that help users store, describe, query, and process data.
blaze.summary: NumPy and Pandas interface to big data

blist.description: Blist is a drop-in replacement for the Python list that provides better performance for large lists and virtually identical performance for small lists. The blist uses a flexible, hybrid array/tree structure to minimize the number of items in memory that are moved. The blist package also provides sortedlist, sortedset, weaksortedlist, weaksortedset, sorteddict, and btuple.
blist.summary: Replacement for Python lists with better performance

blockspring.description: Blockspring helps you get data quickly and easily from a variety of sources. Blockspring for Python allows you to utlize Python to access the utilities, algorithms, API calls, and visualizations in the Blockspring library.

bokeh.description: Bokeh is a Python interactive visualization library that targets modern web browsers for presentation. Its goal is to provide elegant, concise construction of novel graphics in the style of D3.js, and to extend this capability with high-performance interactivity over very large or streaming datasets. Bokeh can help anyone who would like to quickly and easily create interactive plots, dashboards, and data applications.
bokeh.summary: Python interactive visualization library for modern web browsers

boost.description: Boost contains free C++ source libraries that work well with the C++ standard library. The libraries are intended to be widely useful across a broad spectrum of applications.
boost.summary: Boost provides free peer-reviewed portable C++ source libraries.

boto.description: Boto aims to support the full breadth and depth of Amazon Web Services. NOTE: Boto3, the next version of Boto, is stable and recommended for general use.

boto3.description: Boto3 makes it easy to integrate you Python application, library or script with AWS services. It allows Python developers to write softare that makes use of services like Amazon S3 and Amazon EC2.
boto3.summary: Amazon Web Services SDK for Python

botocore.description: Provides the core functionality of Boto3, the AWS SDK for Python

bottlechest.description: Bottlechest is a fork of Bottleneck, a collection of fast NumPy array functions written in Cython. It is specialized for use in Orange.
bottlechest.summary: fast NumPy array functions specialized for use in Orange

bottleneck.description: Bottleneck is a collection of fast NumPy array functions written in Cython.
bottleneck.summary: Fast NumPy array functions written in Cython.

bsddb.description: Bsddb provides an interface to the Berekeley DB library. Users can create hash, btree, or record based library files. Bsddb objects behave generally like dictionaries.
bsddb.summary: The bsddb module provides an interface to the Berkeley DB library

bsdiff4.summary: binary diff and patch using the BSDIFF4-format

btrees.description: BTrees contains a set of persistent object containers built around a modified BTree data structure. The trees are optimized for use inside ZODB's "optimistic currency" paradigm, and include explicit resolution of conflicts detected by that mechanism.

bz2file.description: Bz2file is a Python library for reading and writing bzip2-compressed files. It contains a drop-in replacement for the file interface in the standard library's bz2 module.
bz2file.summary: library for reading and writing bzip2-compressed files

bzip2.description: Bzip2 is a freely available high-quality data compressor. It typically compresses files to within 10% to 15% of the best available techniques, whilst being around twice as fast at compression and six times faster at decompression.

cachecontrol.description: CacheControl is a port of the caching algortihms in httplib2 for use with requests session object.
cachecontrol.summary: httplib2 caching algorithms for use with requests

cached-property.description: Cached-property is a decorator for caching properties in classes. It makes caching of time or computational expensive properties quick and easy.
cached-property.summary: A decorator for caching properties in classes

cairo.description: Cairo is a 2D graphics library with support for multiple output devices. It is designed to produce consistent output on all output media while taking advantage of display hardware acceleration when available.
cairo.summary: A 2D graphics library with support for multiple output devices

casuarius.description: Casuarius is a Cython wrapper for the Cassowary incremental constraint solver.
casuarius.summary: Cython bindings for the Cassowary Constraint Solving Toolkit

cdecimal.description: Cdecimal is a fast drop-in replacement for the decimal module in Python's standard library. Typical performance gains are between 30x for I/O heavy benchmarks and 80x for numerical programs.

certifi.description: Certifi is a curated collection of Root Certificates for validating the trustworthiness of SSL certificates while verifying the identity of TLS hosts.
certifi.summary: Python package for providing Mozilla's CA Bundle.

cffi.description: Cffi aims to allow users to call C code from Python without having to learn a 3rd language. It provides a convenient and reliable way to call compiled C code from Python using interface declarations written in C.
cffi.summary: C Foreign Function Interface for Python

chalmers.description: Chalmers allows you to monitor and control a number of processes. This includes process control, system init, keeping your programs alive, and logging.
chalmers.summary: Monitor and control a number of processes on any operating system

chameleon.description: Chameleon is an HTML/XML template engine for Python designed to generate the document output of a web application, typically HTML markup or XML.

chardet.description: Chardet is the Universal Character Encoding Detector for Python 2 and 3.
chardet.license: GNU Library or Lesser General Public License

cheetah.description: Cheetah is a Python-Powered template engine and code generation tool. It can be used standalone or combined with other tools and frameworks. Its principle use is web development, but Cheetah can also be used to generate C++ game code, Java, SQL, form emails, and Python code.
cheetah.summary: Cheetah is a template engine and code generation tool.

cherrypy.description: Cherrypy allows developers to build web applications in much the same way they would build any other object-oriented Python program. This results in smaller source code developed in less time.

chest.description: Chest acts like a dictionary, but it can write its contents to disk. This is useful because Chest can then hold datasets that are larger than memory, and Chest persists and so can be saved and loaded for later use.
chest.summary: A dictionary that writes its contents to disk

chrpath.description: chrpath is a command line tool to adjust the RPATH or RUNPATH of ELF binaries.
chrpath.summary: Tool to edit the rpath in ELF binaries

click.description: Click is a Python package for creating beautiful command line interfaces in a composable way with as little code as necessary. It aims to make the process of writing command line tools quick and fun.

cligj.description: Cligj is for Python developers who create command line interfaces for geospatial data. Cligj allows you to quickly build consistent, well-tested and interoperable CLIs for handling GeoJSON.

cloudpickle.description: Cloudpickle makes it possible to serialize Python constructs not supported by the default pickle module from the Python standard library. Cloudpickle is especially useful for cluster computing where Python expressions are shipped over the network to execute on remote hosts, possibly close to the data.
cloudpickle.summary: Extended pickling support for Python objects

clyent.description: Clyent is a python command line utility library for binstar, binstar-build, and chalmers.
clyent.summary: Command line client library for windows and posix

cmake.description: CMake is used to control the software compilation process using simple platform and compiler independent configuration files, and generate native makefiles and workspaces that can be used in the compiler environment of your choice.
cmake.summary: A family of tools designed to build, test, and package software

colander.description: Colander is a serialization/deserialization/validation library for strings, mappings, and lists. It is useful as a system for validating and deserializing data obtained via XML, JSON, an HTML form post, or any other equally simple data serialization.
colander.summary: A serialization, deserialization, and validation library

colorama.description: Makes ANSI escape character sequences (for producing colored terminal text and cursor positioning) work under MS Windows.
colorama.summary: Cross-platform colored terminal text in Python

comtypes.description: comtypes is a pure Python COM package based on the ctypes ffi foreign function library. The comtypes package makes it easy to access and implement both custom and dispatch based COM interfaces.

conda.description: Conda is an open source package management system and environment management system for installing multiple versions of software packages and their dependencies and switching easily between them. It works on Linux, OS X and Windows, and was created for Python programs but can package and distribute any software.
conda.summary: Package management system and Environment management system

conda-api.description: Conda-api documents a well-defined small and useful interface to conda, which is stable across many conda versions. It also allows users to easily interact conda from any environment.
conda-api.summary: A light weight conda interface library

conda-build.description: Conda-build contains commands and tools to allow you to build your own packages for conda.
conda-build.summary: Commands and tools for building conda packages

conda-env.description: Provides the conda env interface to Conda environments. All of the usage is documented via the --help flag.
conda-env.summary: Provides a unified interface to dealing with Conda environments

configobj.description: ConfigObj is a simple but powerful config file reader and writer. Its main feature is that it is very easy to use, with a straightforward programmer's interface and a simple syntax for config files. It has many other useful features, including nested sections, list values, multiple line values, string interpolation, and much more.
configobj.summary: Config file reading, writing and validation

configparser.summary: brings the updated configparser from Python 3.5 to Python 2.6-3.5

console_shortcut.summary: Console shortcut creator for Windows (using menuinst)

contextlib2.description: Contextlib2 provides backports of features in the latest version of the standard library's contextlib module to earlier Python versions. It also serves as a real world proving ground for potential future enhancements to that module.
contextlib2.summary: backports and enhancements for the contextlib module

cornice.description: Cornice provides helpers to build & document REST-ish Web Services with Pyramid, with decent default behaviors. It takes care of following the HTTP specification in an automated way where possible.
cornice.summary: build and document Web Services with Pyramid

coverage.description: Coverage.py is a tool for measuring code coverage of Python programs. It monitors your program, noting which parts of the code have been executed, then analyzes the source to identify code that could have been executed but was not. Coverage measurement is typically used to gauge the effectiveness of tests. It can show which parts of your code are being exercised by tests, and which are not.

cryptacular.description: Cryptacular is a collection of strong password hashing functions that share a common interface, and a nice way to use bcrypt as a password hash.
cryptacular.summary: password hashing framework with bcrypt and pbkdf2

cryptography.description: Cryptography is a Python library which exposes cryptographic recipes and primitives. The goal is for it to be your "cryptographic standard library".
cryptography.summary: Provides cryptographic recipes and primitives to Python developers

cssselect.description: Cssselect parses CSS3 Selectors and translate them to XPath 1.0 expressions. Such expressions can be used in lxml or another XPath engine to find the matching elements in an XML or HTML document.
cssselect.summary: cssselect parses CSS3 Selectors and translates them to XPath 1.0

csvkit.description: Csvkit is a suite of utilities for converting to and working with CSV, the king of tabular file formats.
csvkit.summary: utilities for working with CSV, the king of tabular file formats

cubes.description: Cubes is a light-weight Python framework and set of tools for Online Analytical Processing (OLAP), multidimensional analysis, and browsing of aggregated data.
cubes.summary: A light-weight Python OLAP framework for data warehouses

curl.description: Curl is an open source command line tool and library for transferring data with URL syntax. It is used in command lines or scripts to transfer data.
curl.summary: Tool and library for transferring data with URL syntax

cvxcanon.description: Convex optimization modeling tools like CVX, CVXPY, and Convex.Jl translate high-level problem descriptions into low-level, canonical forms that are then passed to an backend solver. CVXcanon is a software package that factors out the common operations that all such modeling systems perform into a single library with a simple C++ interface.
cvxcanon.summary: Low-level library to perform the matrix building step in CVXPY

cvxopt.description: CVXOPT is a free software package for convex optimization based on Python. It can be used with the interactive Python interpreter, on the command line by executing Python scripts, or integrated in other software via Python extension modules. Its main purpose is to make the development of software for convex optimization applications straightforward by building on Python's extensive standard library and on the strengths of Python as a high-level programming language.

cycler.description: Cycler is a package used to create composable style cycles.

cymem.description: Cymem provides two small memory-management helpers for Cython. They make it easy to tie memory to a Python object's life-cycle, so that the memory is freed when the object is garbage collected.
cymem.summary: Manage calls to malloc/free through Cython

cython.description: Cython is an optimising static compiler for both the Python programming language and the extended Cython programming language. It makes writing C extensions for Python as easy as Python itself.
cython.summary: The Cython compiler for writing C extensions for the Python language

cytoolz.description: CyToolz is the Cython implementation of the toolz package, which provides high performance utility functions for iterables, functions, and dictionaries.
cytoolz.summary: Cython implementation of Toolz, high performance functional utilities

dask.description: Dask is a simple task scheduling system that uses directed acylcic graphs (DAGS) of tasks to break up large computations into many small ones. Dask enables parallel computing through task scheduling and blocked algorithms. This allows developers to write complex parallel algorithms and execute them in parallel either on a modern multi-core machine or on a distributed cluster.
dask.summary: Task scheduling and blocked algorithms for parallel processing

datashader.summary: graphics pipeline system for creating representations of large amounts

datashape.description: Datashape is a language for describing data. It is an extension of the NumPy dtype with an emphasis on cross language support.
datashape.summary: Language defining a data description protocol

datrie.summary: Super-fast, efficiently stored Trie for Python, uses libdatrie

db.description: Oracle Berkeley DB provides the best open source embeddable databases allowing developers the choice of SQL, Key/Value, XML/XQuery, or Java Object storage for their data model. At its core is a fast, scalable transactional database engine with proven reliability and availability.

dbf.description: Dbf is a pure Python package for reading/writing dBase, FoxPro, and Visual FoxPro .dbf files. Currently supports dBase III, Clipper, FoxPro, and Visual FoxPro tables. Text is returned as unicode, and codepage settings in tables are honored.
dbf.summary: Reading/writing dBase, FoxPro, and Visual FoxPro .dbf files

decorator.description: Preserve the signature of decorated functions in a consistent way across Python releases.
decorator.summary: Better living through Python with decorators

dill.description: Dill extends Python's 'pickle' module for serializing and de-serializing Python objects to he majority of the built-in python types. Serialization is the process of converting an object to a byte stream, and the inverse of which is converting a byte stream back to on python object hierarchy.

distributed.description: Distributed is a ightweight library for distributed computing in Python. It extends both the concurrent.futures and dask APIs to moderate sized clusters. Distributed provides data-local computation by keeping data on worker nodes, running computations where data lives, and by managing complex data dependencies between tasks.
distributed.summary: Lightweight library for distributed computing in Python

django.description: Django is a high-level Python Web framework that encourages rapid development and clean, pragmatic design. Built by experienced developers, it takes care of much of the hassle of Web development, so you can focus on writing your app without needing to reinvent the wheel.
django.summary: Web framework that encourages rapid development

dnspython.description: dnspython is a DNS toolkit for Python. It supports almost all record types. It can be used for queries, zone transfers, and dynamic updates. It supports TSIG authenticated messages and EDNS0.

docopt.description: Docopt helps you create beautiful command-line interfaces easily. Docopt will help you define interface for your command-line app and automatically generate a parser for it.

docutils.description: Docutils is an open-source text processing system for processing plaintext documentation into useful formats, such as HTML, LaTeX, man-pages, open- document, or XML. It includes reStructuredText, the easy to read, easy to use, what-you-see-is-what-you-get plaintext markup language.
docutils.summary: Utilities for general- and special-purpose documentation

drmaa.description: Distributed Resource Management Application API (DRMAA) bindings for Python.
drmaa.summary: Python wrapper around the C DRMAA library

dynd-python.description: DyND-Python is the Python exposure of the DyND dynamic mult-dimensional array library.
dynd-python.summary: Python exposure of DyND, a library for dynamic arrays

ecdsa.description: This is an easy-to-use implementation of ECDSA cryptography (Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm), implemented purely in Python, released under the MIT license. With this library, you can quickly create keypairs (signing key and verifying key), sign messages, and verify the signatures. The keys and signatures are very short, making them easy to handle and incorporate into other protocols.

ecos.description: ECOS is a numerical software for solving convex second-order cone programs (SOCPs).

enaml.description: Enaml is a programming language and framework for creating professional quality user interfaces with minimal effort. Enaml combines a domain specific declarative language with a constraints based layout system to allow users to easily define rich UIs with complex and flexible layouts. Enaml applications can be run on any platform which supports Python and Qt.
enaml.summary: Declarative DSL for building rich user interfaces in Python

enum34.description: This module defines two enumeration classes that can be used to define unique sets of names and values. It also defines one decorator.
enum34.summary: Robust enumerated type support in Python

ephem.description: PyEphem provides basic astronomical computations for the Python programming language. Given a date and location on the Earth's surface, it can compute the positions of the Sun and Moon, of the planets and their moons, and of any asteroids, comets, or earth satellites whose orbital elements the user can provide.

essbasepy.description: The MaxL Python Module, Essbase.py, provides access to Hyperion Essbase multi-dimensional databases from Python programs through MaxL. It is similar in function and usage to the Perl module Essbase.pm.
essbasepy.summary: access to Oracle Essbase multi-dimensional databases using MaxL

et_xmlfile.description: Et_xmlfile is a low memory streaming XML generator developed for compatibility with lxml.etree.xmlfile where this is not available. It is pure Python and about twice as slow than lxml or other solutions.
et_xmlfile.summary: Low memory library for creating large XML files

execnet.description: Execnet provides a share-nothing model with channel-send/receive communication for distributing execution across many Python interpreters across ersion, platform and network barriers.

expat.description: Expat is an XML parser library written in C. It is a stream-oriented parser in which an application registers handlers for things the parser might find in the XML document (like start tags).
expat.summary: XML parser library written in C

fabric.description: Fabric is a Python ibrary and command-line tool for streamlining the use of SSH for application deployment or systems administration tasks.
fabric.summary: A  simple, Pythonic tool for remote execution and deployment

fastcache.description: C implementation of Python 3 functools.lru_cache. Provides speedup of 10- 30x over standard library.

faulthandler.description: Fault handler for SIGSEGV, SIGFPE, SIGABRT, SIGBUS and SIGILL signals: display the Python traceback and restor the previous handler on a crash.
faulthandler.summary: Display the Python traceback on a crash

feedparser.description: Feedparser is a Universal Feed Parser for Python. It is used to download and parse syndicated feeds.

flake8.description: Flake8 is a wrapper around Pyflakes, pep8, and Ned Batchelder's McCabe script. Flake8 runs all the tools by launching the single flake8 script. It displays the warnings in a per-file, merged output.
flake8.summary: Modular source code checker for pep8, pyflakes and co

flask.description: Flask is a microframework for Python based on Werkzeug and Jinja2. It's intended for getting started very quickly and was developed with best intentions in mind.
flask.summary: A microframework based on Werkzeug, Jinja2 and good intentions

flask-cors.description: A Flask extension for handling Cross Origin Resource Sharing (CORS), making cross-origin AJAX possible. This package exposes a Flask extension which by default enables CORS support on all routes, for all origins and methods.
flask-cors.summary: Flask extension adding a decorator for CORS support

flask-login.description: Flask-Login provides user session management for Flask. It handles the common tasks of logging in, logging out, and remembering your users' sessions over extended periods of time.

flask-wtf.description: Flask-WTF is a simple integration of Flask and WTForms, including CSRF, file upload, and Recaptcha integration.
flask-wtf.summary: Simple integration of Flask and WTForms

fontconfig.description: Fontconfig is a library designed to provide system-wide font configuration, customization and application access.
fontconfig.summary: A library for configuring and customizing font access

freeglut.description: FreeGLUT is a free-software/open-source alternative to the OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT) library. GLUT (and hence FreeGLUT) takes care of all the system-specific chores required for creating windows, initializing OpenGL contexts, and handling input events, to allow for trully portable OpenGL programs.
freeglut.summary: An alternative to the OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT) library

freeimage.description: FreeImage is an Open Source library project for developers who would like to support popular graphics image formats like PNG, BMP, JPEG, TIFF and others as needed by today's multimedia applications. FreeImage is easy to use, fast, multithreading safe, compatible with all 32-bit or 64-bit versions of Windows, and cross-platform (works both with Linux and Mac OS X).
freeimage.summary: Supports popular graphics image formats like PNG, BMP, JPEG, TIFF

freetype.description: FreeType 2 is a software font engine that is designed to be small, efficient, highly customizable, and portable while capable of producing high-quality output (glyph images). It can be used in graphics libraries, display servers, font conversion tools, text image generation tools, and many other products as well.
freetype.summary: A Free, High-Quality, and Portable Font Engine

funcsigs.description: Funcsigs is a backport of the PEP 362 function signature features from Python 3.3's inspect module. The backport is also compatible with Python 2.6, 2.7, and 3.2 and up.
funcsigs.summary: Python function signatures from PEP362 for Python 2.6, 2.7 and 3.2+

functools32.description: Functools32 is a backport of the Python 3.2 functools module for use on Python versions 2.7 and PyPy. It includes new features lru_cache (Least-recently-used cache decorator).
functools32.summary: backport of the functools module from Python 3.2.3 for use on 2.7

future.description: Python-future is the missing compatibility layer between Python 2 and Python 3. t allows you to use a single, clean Python 3.x-compatible codebase to support both Python 2 and Python 3 with minimal overhead.
future.summary: Clean single-source support for Python 3 and 2

futures.description: The concurrent.futures module provides a high-level interface for asynchronously executing callables.
futures.summary: A Java-style futures package for Python

gdata.description: The Google data Python client library makes it easy to interact with Google services through the Google Data APIs.
gdata.summary: Python client library for Google data APIs

gdbm.description: GDBM is a library of database functions that use extensible hashing and work similar to the standard UNIX dbm. These routines are provided to a programmer needing to create and manipulate a hashed database.

gensim.description: Gensim is a Python library for topic modelling, document indexing and similarity retrieval with large corpora. Target audience is the natural language processing (NLP) and information retrieval (IR) community.

geos.description: GEOS (Geometry Engine - Open Source) is a C++ port of the Java Topology Suite (JTS). As such, it aims to contain the complete functionality of JTS in C++.
geos.summary: A C++ port of the Java Topology Suite (JTS)

get_terminal_size.summary: backport of the get_terminal_size function from Python 3.3

gevent.description: Gevent is a coroutine -based Python networking library that uses greenlet to provide a high-level synchronous API on top of the libev event loop.

gevent-websocket.description: Gevent-websocket is a WebSocket library for the gevent networking library.
gevent-websocket.summary: A WebSocket library for the gevent networking library

git.description: Git is a free and open source distributed version control system designed to handle everything from small to very large projects with speed and efficiency.

glib.description: GLib provides the core application building blocks for libraries and applications written in C. It provides the core object system used in GNOME, the main loop implementation, and a large set of utility functions for strings and common data structures.
glib.summary: Core application building blocks for libraries and applications in C

glueviz.description: Glue is a Python library to explore relationships within and among related datasets. Its main features include Linked Statistical Graphics, flexible linking across data, and full scripting capability.

googlecl.description: 8 June 2015: GoogleCL is currently broken due to the OAuth1 turndown, and likely to remain so.
googlecl.summary: Brings Google services to the command line

graphite-web.description: Graphite-web is a highly scalable real-time graphing system. It is a Django-based web application that renders graphs and dashboards.

graphviz.description: Graphviz is open source graph visualization software. Graph visualization is a way of representing structural information as diagrams of abstract graphs and networks.

greenlet.description: A "greenlet" is a still more primitive notion of micro-thread with no implicit scheduling; coroutines, in other words. This is useful when you want to control exactly when your code runs.

gridmap.description: GridMap allows you to easily create jobs on the cluster directly from Python. You can directly map Python functions onto the cluster without needing to write any wrapper code yourself.
gridmap.summary: Map Python functions onto a cluster using a grid engine

grin.description: Grin is Robert Kern's enhanced grep-like tool analagous to ack(-grep) (perl), rak (ruby), and ag (C).

gunicorn.description: Gunicorn 'Green Unicorn' is a Python WSGI HTTP Server for UNIX. It's a pre-fork worker model ported from Ruby's Unicorn project. The Gunicorn server is broadly compatible with various web frameworks, simply implemented, light on server resources, and fairly speedy.
gunicorn.summary: Python WSGI HTTP Server for UNIX

h5py.description: The h5py package is a Pythonic interface to the HDF5 binary data format. It lets you store huge amounts of numerical data, and easily manipulate that data from NumPy. For example, you can slice into multi-terabyte datasets stored on disk, as if they were real NumPy arrays. Thousands of datasets can be stored in a single file, categorized and tagged however you want.
h5py.summary: Pythonic interface to the HDF5 binary data format

harfbuzz.description: HarfBuzz is a text shaping library. New Harbuzz targets various font technologies while Old HarfBuzz targets only OpenType fonts.

hdf4.description: At its lowest level, HDF is a physical file format for storing scientific data. At its highest level, HDF is a collection of utilities and applications for manipulating, viewing, and analyzing data in HDF files. pycrypto.description: pycrpto, the Python Cryptography Toolkit, is a collection of both secure hash functions and various encryption algorithms.

pycurl.description: PycURL can be used to fetch objects identified by a URL from a Python program, similar to the urllib Python module. PycURL is mature, very fast, and supports a lot of features.

pyflakes.description: Pyflakes is similar to PyChecker in scope, but differs in that it does not execute the modules to check them. This is both safer and faster, although it does not perform as many checks. Unlike PyLint, Pyflakes checks only for logical errors in programs; it does not perform any check on style.
pyflakes.summary: Checks Python source files for errors

pygments.description: Pygments is a generic syntax highlighter suitable for use in code hosting, forums, wikis or other applications that need to prettify source code.

pylint.description: Pylint is a tool that checks for errors in Python code, tries to enforce a coding standard and looks for bad code smells. This is similar but nevertheless different from what pychecker provides, especially since pychecker explicitly does not bother with coding style.

pymc.description: PyMC is a python module that implements Bayesian statistical models and fitting algorithms, including Markov chain Monte Carlo.

pymongo.description: The PyMongo distribution contains tools for interacting with MongoDB database from Python. The bson package is an implementation of the BSON format for Python. The pymongo package is a native Python driver for MongoDB. The gridfs package is a gridfs implementation on top of pymongo.

pymysql.description: PyMySQL is a pure-Python MySQL client library. The goal of PyMySQL is to be a drop-in replacement for MySQLdb and work on CPython, PyPy and IronPython.

pyodbc.description: pyodbc is a Python 2.x and 3.x module that allows you to use ODBC to connect to almost any database from Windows, Linux, OS/X, and more.

pyopengl.description: PyOpenGL is the most common cross platform Python binding to OpenGL and related APIs. The binding is created using the standard ctypes library.

pyopengl-accelerate.description: PyOpenGL is the most common cross platform Python binding to OpenGL and related APIs. The binding is created using the standard ctypes library.

pyopenssl.description: pyOpenSSL is a high-level wrapper around a subset of the OpenSSL library. It includes: -SSL.Connection objects, wrapping the methods of Python's portable sockets -Callbacks written in Python -Extensive error-handling mechanism, mirroring OpenSSL's error codes and much more.
pyopenssl.summary: Python wrapper module around the OpenSSL library

pyparsing.description: The pyparsing module is an alternative approach to creating and executing simple grammars, vs. the traditional lex/yacc approach, or the use of regular expressions. The pyparsing module provides a library of classes that client code uses to construct the grammar directly in Python code.

pyproj.description: Pyproj is a Cython wrapper to provide python interfaces to PROJ.4 functions. It performs cartographic transformations and geodetic computations.
pyproj.summary: Python interface to PROJ4 library for cartographic transformations

pyqt.description: PyQt is a set of Python v2 and v3 bindings for The Qt Company's Qt application framework and runs on all platforms supported by Qt including Windows, MacOS/X and Linux. PyQt5 supports Qt v5. PyQt4 supports Qt v4 and will build against Qt v5. The bindings are implemented as a set of Python modules and contain over 1,000 classes.
pyqt.summary: Python binding of the cross-platform GUI toolkit Qt

pyqtgraph.description: PyQtGraph is a pure-python graphics and GUI library built on PyQt4 / PySide and numpy. It is intended for use in mathematics / scientific / engineering applications. Despite being written entirely in python, the library is very fast due to its heavy leverage of numpy for number crunching and Qt's GraphicsView framework for fast display.
pyqtgraph.summary: Scientific Graphics and GUI Library for Python

pyramid.description: Pyramid is a very general open source Python web framework. As a framework, its primary job is to make it easier for a developer to create an arbitrary web application. The type of application being created isn't really important; it could be a spreadsheet, a corporate intranet, or a social networking platform. Pyramid is general enough that it can be used in a wide variety of circumstances.
pyramid.summary: The Pyramid Web Framework, a Pylons project

pyramid_chameleon.description: pyramid_chameleon is a set of bindings that make templates written for the Chameleon templating system work under the Pyramid web framework.
pyramid_chameleon.summary: Bindings for the Chameleon templating system for Pyramid

pyramid_debugtoolbar.description: pyramid_debugtoolbar provides a useful debug toolbar while you're developing a Pyramid application.
pyramid_debugtoolbar.summary: interactive HTML debugger for Pyramid application development

pyramid_jinja2.description: pyramid_jinja2 is a set of bindings that make templates written for the Jinja2 templating system work under the Pyramid web framework.
pyramid_jinja2.summary: Jinja2 template bindings for the Pyramid web framework

pyramid_mako.description: pyramid_mako is a set of bindings that makes templates written for the Mako templating system work under the Pyramid web framework.
pyramid_mako.summary: Mako template bindings for the Pyramid web framework

pyramid_tm.description: pyramid_tm allows Pyramid requests to join the active transaction as provided by the Python transaction package.
pyramid_tm.summary: Allows Pyramid requests to join the active transaction

pyreadline.description: The pyreadline package is a python implementation of GNU readline functionality it is based on the ctypes based UNC readline package. It is not complete. It has been tested for use with Windows 2000 and Windows XP.

pysal.description: PySAL(Python Spatial Analysis Library) is an open source library of spatial analysis functions written in Python intended to support the development of high level applications.

pysam.description: Pysam is a python module for reading and manipulating Samfiles. It's a lightweight wrapper of the samtools C-API. Pysam also includes an interface for tabix.
pysam.summary: Python module for reading and manipulating Samfiles

pyserial.description: pySerial encapsulates the access for the serial port. It provides backends for Python running on Windows, OSX, Linux, BSD (possibly any POSIX compliant system) and IronPython. The module named "serial" automatically selects the appropriate backend.

pysnmp.description: PySNMP is a cross-platform, pure-Python SNMP engine implementation. It features fully-functional SNMP engine capable to act in Agent/Manager/Proxy roles, talking SNMP v1/v2c/v3 protocol versions over IPv4/IPv6 and other network transports.

pystan.description: PyStan provides a Python interface to Stan, a package for Bayesian inference using the No-U-Turn sampler, a variant of Hamiltonian Monte Carlo.

pytables.description: PyTables is a package for managing hierarchical datasets and designed to efficiently and easily cope with extremely large amounts of data. PyTables is built on top of the HDF5 library, using the Python language and the NumPy package.
pytables.summary: Manage hierarchical datasets to cope with large amounts of data

pytest.description: The pytest framework makes it easy to write small tests, yet scales to support complex functional testing for applications and libraries.
pytest.summary: Simple and powerful testing with Python

pytest-cache.description: NOTE: pytest-cache is no longer maintained since its functionality was integrated into pytest core starting with pytest-2.8.0.
pytest-cache.summary: pytest plugin with mechanisms for caching across test runs

pytest-pep8.summary: pytest plugin to check PEP8 requirements

python.description: Python is a widely used high-level, general-purpose, interpreted, dynamic programming language. Its design philosophy emphasizes code readability, and its syntax allows programmers to express concepts in fewer lines of code than would be possible in languages such as C++ or Java. The language provides constructs intended to enable clear programs on both a small and large scale.

python-daemon.description: Python-daemon implements the well-behaved daemon specification of PEP 3143, "Standard daemon process library".
python-daemon.summary: Library to implement a well-behaved Unix daemon process

python-dateutil.description: The dateutil module provides powerful extensions to the standard datetime module, available in Python.
python-dateutil.summary: Extensions to the standard Python datetime module

python-gdbm.description: The gdbm module provides an interface to the GNU DBM library. gdbm objects behave like mappings (dictionaries), except that keys and values are always strings.

python-ntlm.description: Python-nltm provides NTLM support, including an authentication handler for urllib2. This library allows you to retrieve content from (usually corporate) servers protected with windows authentication (NTLM) using the Python urllib2.

python.app.summary: Proxy on OS X letting Python libraries hook into the gui event loop

pytz.description: pytz brings the Olson tz database into Python. This library allows accurate and cross platform timezone calculations using Python 2.4 or higher. It also solves the issue of ambiguous times at the end of daylight saving time.
pytz.summary: World timezone definitions, modern and historical

pyyaml.description: PyYAML is a YAML parser and emitter for Python. YAML is a data serialization format designed for human readability and interaction with scripting languages.
pyyaml.summary: YAML parser and emitter for Python

pyzmq.description: PyZMQ contains Python bindings for 0MQ. 0MQ is a lightweight and fast messaging implementation.

qgrid.description: Qgrid is an IPython widget which uses SlickGrid to render pandas DataFrames within a Jupyter notebook. This allows you to explore your DataFrames with intuitive scrolling, sorting, and filtering controls, as well as edit your DataFrames by double clicking a cell.
qgrid.summary: Pandas DataFrame viewer for IPython Notebook

qt.description: Qt helps you create connected devices, UIs & applications that run anywhere on any device, on any operating system at any time.
qt.summary: Qt is a cross-platform application and UI framework

qtconsole.description: A rich Qt-based console for working with Jupyter kernels, supporting rich media output, session export, and more. The Qt console is a very lightweight application that largely feels like a terminal, but provides a number of enhancements only possible in a GUI, such as inline figures, proper multiline editing with syntax highlighting, graphical calltips, and more.

qtpy.summary: uniform layer to support PyQt4, PyQt5 and PySide with a single codebase

quandl.description: Quandl helps data analysts save time, effort and money by delivering high-quality financial and economic data in the precise format they need.
quandl.summary: High quality financial and economic data

queuelib.description: Queuelib is a collection of persistent (disk-based) queues for Python. Queuelib goals are speed and simplicity.

readline.description: The GNU Readline library provides a set of functions for use by applications that allow users to edit command lines as they are typed in. Both Emacs and vi editing modes are available. The Readline library includes additional functions to maintain a list of previously-entered command lines, to recall and perhaps reedit those lines, and perform csh-like history expansion on previous commands.
readline.summary: Line-editing for programs with a command-line interface

redis.description: Redis is an open source (BSD licensed), in-memory data structure store, used as database, cache and message broker. It supports data structures such as strings, hashes, lists, sets, sorted sets with range queries, bitmaps, hyperloglogs and geospatial indexes with radius queries.

redis-py.description: The Python interface to the Redis key-value store. Requires a running Redis server.

reportlab.description: The ReportLab toolkit is a collection of open source Python language modules organised and supported by ReportLab. The modules are primarily concerned with automating methods for generating Portable Document Format (PDF) files, but there is also a cross-platform vector graphics library able to generate bitmap and vector charts and drawings.

repoze.lru.description: The Repoze project is a collection of technologies which bridges the WSGI and Zope worlds.
repoze.lru.summary: A tiny LRU cache implementation and decorator

requests.description: Requests is the only Non-GMO HTTP library for Python, safe for human consumption.

routes.description: Routes is a Python re-implementation of the Rails routes system for mapping URL's to Controllers/Actions and generating URL's. Routes makes it easy to create pretty and concise URL's that are RESTful with little effort.

runipy.description: runipy allows you to run IPython notebooks as command-line scripts, generate HTML reports, and automate data pipelines.
runipy.summary: Run IPython notebooks from the command line

sas7bdat.description: sas7bdat will read sas7bdat files using pure Python (2.6+, 3+). No SAS software required!

scikit-bio.description: scikit-bio is an open-source, BSD-licensed, python package providing data structures, algorithms, and educational resources for bioinformatics.

scikit-image.description: The scikit-image SciKit (toolkit for SciPy) extends scipy.ndimage to provide a versatile set of image processing routines.

scikit-learn.summary: A set of python modules for machine learning and data mining

scikit-rf.description: scikit-rf is an Open Source, BSD-licensed package for RF/Microwave engineering implemented in the Python programming language. It provides a modern, object-oriented library which is both flexible and scalable.

scipy.description: SciPy is a Python-based ecosystem of open-source software for mathematics, science, and engineering.

scrapy.description: Scrapy is an open source and collaborative framework for extracting the data you need from websites in a fast, simple, yet extensible way.
scrapy.summary: A high-level Python Screen Scraping framework

seaborn.description: Seaborn is a Python visualization library based on matplotlib. It provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive statistical graphics.

semantic_version.description: This small python library provides a few tools to handle SemVer in Python.

semver.summary: Python package to work with Semantic Versioning

serf.description: The serf library is a high performance C-based HTTP client library built upon the Apache Portable Runtime (APR) library.
serf.summary: High performance C-based HTTP client library

service_identity.description: service_identity aspires to give you all the tools you need for verifying whether a certificate is valid for the intended purposes.

setuptools.description: Setuptools is a fully-featured, actively-maintained, and stable library designed to facilitate packaging Python projects.
setuptools.summary: Download, build, install, upgrade, and uninstall Python packages

setuptools_scm.description: setuptools_scm handles managing your python package versions in scm metadata instead of declaring them as the version argument or in a scm managed file.
setuptools_scm.summary: Manage your versions by scm tags

sh.description: sh is a full-fledged subprocess interface for Python that allows you to call any program as if it were a function.

shapely.description: Shapely is a Python package for manipulation and analysis of geometric objects in the Cartesian plane.

simplegeneric.description: The simplegeneric module lets you define simple single-dispatch generic functions, akin to Python's built-in generic functions like len(), iter() and so on. However, instead of using specially-named methods, these generic functions use simple lookup tables, akin to those used by e.g. pickle.dump() and other generic functions found in the Python standard library.

simplejson.description: simplejson is a simple, fast, complete, correct and extensible JSON encoder and decoder for Python 2.5+ and Python 3.3+. It is pure Python code with no dependencies, but includes an optional C extension for a serious speed boost.
simplejson.summary: Simple, fast, extensible JSON encoder/decoder for Python

singledispatch.description: This library brings functools.singledispatch from Python 3.4 to Python 2.6-3.3.
singledispatch.summary: Transforms a function into a single-dispatch generic function

sip.description: SIP is a tool that makes it very easy to create Python bindings for C and C++ libraries. SIP comprises a code generator and a Python module. The code generator processes a set of specification files and generates C or C++ code which is then compiled to create the bindings extension module. The SIP Python module provides support functions to the automatically generated code.
sip.summary: Create Python bindings for C and C++ libraries

six.description: Six provides simple utilities for wrapping over differences between Python 2 and Python 3. It is intended to support codebases that work on both Python 2 and 3 without modification. six consists of only one Python file, so it is painless to copy into a project.

smart_open.description: smart_open is a Python 2 & Python 3 library for efficient streaming of very large files from/to S3, HDFS, WebHDFS or local (compressed) files.

snakebite.description: Snakebite is a python library that provides a pure python HDFS client and a wrapper around Hadoops minicluster. The client uses protobuf for communicating with the NameNode and comes in the form of a library and a command line interface.

snakeviz.description: SnakeViz is a browser based graphical viewer for the output of Python's cProfile module.
snakeviz.summary: Web-based viewer for Python profiler output

snowballstemmer.description: Snowball stemmer provides 16 stemmer algorithms generated from Snowball algorithms.
snowballstemmer.summary: Snowball stemming library collection for Python

sockjs-tornado.description: SockJS-tornado is a Python server side counterpart of SockJS-client browser library running on top of Tornado framework.
sockjs-tornado.summary: SockJS python server implementation on top of Tornado framework

spacy.description: spaCy is a library for advanced natural language processing in Python and Cython.

sphinx.description: Sphinx is a tool that makes it easy to create intelligent and beautiful documentation.

sphinx_rtd_theme.description: A mobile-friendly sphinx theme for readthedocs.org.

spyder.description: Spyder is a powerful interactive development environment for the Python language with advanced editing, interactive testing, debugging and introspection features. Additionally, Spyder is a numerical computing environment thanks to the support of IPython and popular Python libraries such as NumPy, SciPy, or matplotlib.

sqlalchemy.description: SQLAlchemy is the Python SQL toolkit and Object Relational Mapper that gives application developers the full power and flexibility of SQL.

sqlite.description: SQLite is a software library that implements a self-contained, serverless, zero-configuration, transactional SQL database engine.

sqlparse.description: sqlparse is a non-validating SQL parser for Python. It provides support for parsing, splitting and formatting SQL statements.
sqlparse.summary: A non-validating SQL parser module for Python

ssh.description: Module for Python 2.6+ that implements the SSH2 protocol for secure (encrypted and authenticated) connections to remote machines.

starcluster.description: StarCluster has been designed to automate and simplify the process of building, configuring, and managing clusters of virtual machines on Amazon's EC2 cloud. StarCluster allows anyone to easily create a cluster computing environment in the cloud suited for distributed and parallel computing applications and systems.
starcluster.summary: Cluster-computing toolkit for Amazon's Elastic Compute Cloud

statsmodels.description: Statsmodels is a Python module that allows users to explore data, estimate statistical models, and perform statistical tests. An extensive list of descriptive statistics, statistical tests, plotting functions, and result statistics are available for different types of data and each estimator. Researchers across fields may find that statsmodels fully meets their needs for statistical computing and data analysis in Python.

suds-jurko.license: GNU Library or Lesser General Public License LGPL

supervisor.description: Supervisor is a client/server system that allows its users to monitor and control a number of processes on UNIX-like operating systems.
supervisor.summary: A system for controlling process state under UNIX

svn.description: Subversion is an open source, centralized version control system.
svn.summary: Enterprise-class centralized version control for the masses

swig.description: SWIG is an interface compiler that connects programs written in C and C++ with scripting languages such as Perl, Python, Ruby, and Tcl. It works by taking the declarations found in C/C++ header files and using them to generate the wrapper code that scripting languages need to access the underlying C/C++ code.
swig.summary: A compiler that integrates C and C++ with a variety of languages

sympy.description: SymPy is a Python library for symbolic mathematics. It aims to become a full-featured computer algebra system (CAS) while keeping the code as simple as possible in order to be comprehensible and easily extensible.

tblib.description: A traceback serialization library allowing you to Pickle tracebacks and raise exceptions with pickled tracebacks in different processes. This allows better error handling when running code over multiple processes.

tempita.description: tempita is a small templating language. This language implements if/elif/else, for/continue/break, expressions, and blocks of Python code.

teradata.description: The Teradata Python Module is a freely available, open source, library for the Python programming language, whose aim is to make it easy to script powerful interactions with Teradata Database. It adopts the philosophy of udaSQL, providing a DevOps focused SQL Execution Engine that allows developers to focus on their SQL and procedural logic without worrying about Operational requirements such as external configuration, query banding, and logging.
teradata.summary: Script powerful interactions with Teradata Database

terminado.description: Terminado is a Tornado websocket backend for the term.js Javascript terminal emulator library.
terminado.summary: Terminals served to term.js using Tornado websockets

thinc.description: thinc is a Cython library for learning models with millions of parameters and dozens of classes.

tk.description: Tcl (Tool Command Language) is a very powerful but easy to learn dynamic programming language, suitable for a very wide range of uses, including web and desktop applications, networking, administration, testing and many more.
tk.summary: Dynamic programming language with GUI elements

toolz.description: Toolz provides a set of utility functions for iterators, functions, and dictionaries. These functions interoperate well and form the building blocks of common data analytic operations. They extend the standard libraries itertools and functools and borrow heavily from the standard libraries of contemporary functional languages.
toolz.summary: List processing tools and functional utilities

tornado.description: Tornado is a Python web framework and asynchronous networking library. By using non-blocking network I/O, Tornado can scale to tens of thousands of open connections, making it ideal for long polling, WebSockets, and other applications that require a long-lived connection to each user.
tornado.summary: A Python web framework and asynchronous networking library

traitlets.description: Traitlets is a framework that lets Python classes have attributes with type checking, dynamically calculated default values, and "on change" callbacks.

transaction.description: A transaction consists of one or more operations that we want to perform as a single action. It's an all or nothing proposition: either all the operations that are part of the transaction are completed successfully or none of them have any effect. In the transaction package, a transaction object represents a running transaction that can be committed or aborted in the end.

translationstring.description: A library used by various Pylons Project packages for internationalization (i18n) duties related to translation.

trollius.summary: port of the Tulip project (asyncio module, PEP 3156)

twisted.description: Twisted is an event-based framework for internet applications, supporting Python 2.7 and Python 3.3+. It includes modules for many different purposes.

ujson.description: UltraJSON is an ultra fast JSON encoder and decoder written in pure C with bindings for Python 2.5+ and 3.
ujson.summary: Ultra fast JSON encoder and decoder for Python

unicodecsv.description: The unicodecsv is a drop-in replacement for Python 2.7's csv module which supports unicode strings without a hassle. Supported versions are python 2.6, 2.7, 3.3, 3.4, 3.5, and pypy 2.4.0.
unicodecsv.summary: Drop-in replacement for csv module which supports unicode strings

unixodbc.description: The unixODBC Project goals are to develop and promote unixODBC to be the definitive standard for ODBC on non MS Windows platforms. This is to include GUI support for both KDE and GNOME.
unixodbc.summary: ODBC (Open Database Connectivity) implementation for Unix

unxutils.summary: Ports of common GNU utilities to native Win32

vcversioner.summary: take version numbers from version control

venusian.description: Venusian is a library which allows framework authors to defer decorator actions. Instead of taking actions when a function (or class) decorator is executed at import time, you can defer the action usually taken by the decorator until a separate "scan" phase.
venusian.summary: A library for deferring decorator actions

virtualenv.description: virtualenv is a tool to create isolated Python environments.

vtk.description: The Visualization Toolkit (VTK) is an open-source, freely available software system for 3D computer graphics, image processing, and visualization. It consists of a C++ class library and several interpreted interface layers including Tcl/Tk, Java, and Python.
vtk.summary: 3D computer graphics, image processing, and visualization

waitress.description: Waitress is meant to be a production-quality pure-Python WSGI server with very acceptable performance. It has no dependencies except ones which live in the Python standard library.
waitress.summary: Production-quality WSGI server with very acceptable performance

webob.description: WebOb is a Python library that provides wrappers around the WSGI request environment, and an object to help create WSGI responses. The objects map much of the specified behavior of HTTP, including header parsing, content negotiation and correct handling of conditional and range requests.

websocket.description: gevent-websocket is a WebSocket library for the gevent networking library.

webtest.description: Webtest wraps any WSGI application and makes it easy to send test requests to that application, without starting up an HTTP server.

werkzeug.description: Werkzeug started as simple collection of various utilities for WSGI applications and has become one of the most advanced WSGI utility modules. It includes a powerful debugger, full-featured request and response objects, HTTP utilities to handle entity tags, cache control headers, HTTP dates, cookie handling, file uploads, a powerful URL routing system and a bunch of community-contributed addon modules.
werkzeug.summary: A WSGI utility library for Python

wheel.description: A wheel is a ZIP-format archive with a specially formatted filename and the .whl extension. It is designed to contain all the files for a PEP 376 compatible install in a way that is very close to the on-disk format. Many packages will be properly installed with only the "Unpack" step (simply extracting the file onto sys.path), and the unpacked archive preserves enough information to "Spread" (copy data and scripts to their final locations) at any later time.

whisper.description: Whisper is a fixed-size database, similar in design and purpose to RRD (round-robin-database). It provides fast, reliable storage of numeric data over time. Whisper allows for higher resolution (seconds per point) of recent data to degrade into lower resolutions for long-term retention of historical data.
whisper.summary: File-based time-series database format for Graphite

whoosh.description: Whoosh is a fast, featureful full-text indexing and searching library implemented in pure Python. Programmers can use it to easily add search functionality to their applications and websites. Every part of how Whoosh works can be extended or replaced to meet your needs exactly.

workerpool.description: The workerpool module is a simple framework for easily distributing jobs into multiple worker threads.

wrapt.description: The aim of the wrapt module is to provide a transparent object proxy for Python, which can be used as the basis for the construction of function wrappers and decorator functions.
wrapt.summary: Module for decorators, wrappers and monkey patching

wtforms.summary: A flexible forms validation and rendering library for Python

xarray.description: xarray is an open source project and Python package that aims to bring the labeled data power of pandas to the physical sciences, by providing N-dimensional variants of the core pandas data structures.
xarray.summary: N-D labeled arrays and datasets in Python

xerces-c.description: Xerces-C++ is a validating XML parser written in a portable subset of C++. Xerces-C++ makes it easy to give your application the ability to read and write XML data.
xerces-c.summary: A validating XML parser written in a portable subset of C++

xlrd.description: Xlrd provides a library or developers to use to extract information from Microsoft Excel (tm) spreadsheet files
xlrd.summary: Extract data from Microsoft Excel spreadsheet files

xlsxwriter.description: XlsxWriter is a Python module for writing files in the Excel 2007+ XLSX file format. XlsxWriter can be used to write text, numbers, formulas and hyperlinks to multiple worksheets and it supports features such as formatting and more.
xlsxwriter.summary: A Python module for creating Excel XLSX files

xlutils.description: Python packages to work with Excel files that will run on any Python platform and that do not require either Windows or Excel to be used.
xlutils.summary: Utilities for working with Excel files

xlwings.description: Replace your VBA code with Python, a powerful yet easy-to-use programming language that is highly suited for numerical analysis.
xlwings.summary: Interact with Excel from Python and vice versa

xlwt.description: Xlwt is a library for developers to use to generate spreadsheet files compatible with Microsoft Excel versions 95 to 2003.
xlwt.summary: Writing data and formatting information to Excel files

xz.description: XZ Utils is free general-purpose data compression software with a high compression ratio. XZ Utils were written for POSIX-like systems, but also work on some not-so-POSIX systems.
xz.summary: Data compression software with high compression ratio

yaml.description: YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language) is a human friendly data serialization standard for all programming languages.
yaml.summary: A human friendly data serialization standard

yt.description: yt is a python package for analyzing and visualizing volumetric, multi-resolution data from astrophysical simulations, radio telescopes, and a burgeoning interdisciplinary community.
yt.summary: An analysis and visualization toolkit for Astrophysical simulations

zeromq.description: ZeroMQ s a high-performance asynchronous messaging library, aimed at use in distributed or concurrent applications.

zlib.description: zlib is designed to be a free, general-purpose, lossless data-compression library for use on virtually any computer hardware and operating system.

zope.deprecation.description: Provides a simple function called deprecated(names, reason) to mark deprecated modules, classes, functions, methods and properties.

zope.interface.description: Provides an implementation of "object interfaces" for Python. Interfaces are a mechanism for labeling objects as conforming to a given API or contract.

zope.sqlalchemy.description: Unify the plethora of existing packages integrating SQLAlchemy with Zope's transaction management.
